GEOMETRIC–STIFFNESS HORIZONS IN DISK GALAXIES
A Structural Origin of the Rotation-Curve Turnover Radius

Author: Martin Ollett
Year: 2026


------------------------------------------------------------
ABSTRACT
------------------------------------------------------------

We investigate the structural origin of the turnover radius Rs in
disk galaxy rotation curves using the SPARC database.

A stiffness–memory framework predicts that the radius where the
rotation curve transitions from baryonic rise to asymptotic
behaviour is controlled by a cumulative structural budget rather
than by dark matter halos or arbitrary fitting functions.

Using 53 well-measured galaxies from SPARC, we test three key
predictions:

1. A simple horizon law predicting Rs from cumulative stiffness
2. A universal rotation-curve master curve once radii are scaled by Rs
3. A geometric–stiffness scaling relation linking Rs to outer disk
   extent and total stiffness budget.

Out-of-sample tests show that the simple horizon law predicts Rs
with a median log RMSE of 0.054 dex. When the resulting Rs is used
to scale rotation curves, a universal master curve reproduces the
observed velocity profiles with median error 0.064 in V/V_inf.

We further find that the turnover radius obeys a structural law

    Rs ∝ r_max * Stot^{-0.40}

where r_max is the outer disk extent and Stot is the cumulative
stiffness budget.

This relation removes residual correlations with stiffness budget
and produces a narrow invariant distribution

    (Rs / r_max) Stot^{0.40} ≈ constant.

These results suggest that the observed rotation-curve structure
may emerge from baryonic geometry and cumulative stiffness rather
than requiring additional unseen mass components.


------------------------------------------------------------
1. INTRODUCTION
------------------------------------------------------------

Galaxy rotation curves exhibit a characteristic transition from a
rising baryonic regime to a quasi-flat outer profile.

In standard cosmology this behaviour is explained through the
presence of dark matter halos.

However, empirical studies have revealed tight correlations
between baryonic structure and rotation-curve properties,
including:

• the baryonic Tully–Fisher relation (BTFR)
• the radial acceleration relation (RAR)
• universal rotation-curve shapes.

These correlations suggest that disk structure itself may encode
the physical scale governing the transition radius.

In this work we test a structural hypothesis:

    the turnover radius Rs is set by a cumulative stiffness budget
    derived from baryonic structure.

Rather than fitting Rs as a free parameter, we attempt to predict
it directly from measurable galaxy properties.


------------------------------------------------------------
2. STIFFNESS–MEMORY FRAMEWORK
------------------------------------------------------------

The stiffness framework models gravitational response as a
spatially varying stiffness field m(r).

For screened curvature systems the potential behaves as

    V(r) ∝ exp(-∫ m(s) ds) / r

so cumulative stiffness

    S(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds

controls energy containment.

The horizon radius R* emerges when a fixed cumulative stiffness
budget is reached.

In disk galaxies we identify this horizon with the rotation-curve
turnover radius Rs.

Key observable quantities used in the analysis include:

Stot
    total cumulative stiffness budget

μS
    local stiffness slope near Rs

τ
    outer disk extent proxy (≈ r_max / Rs)


------------------------------------------------------------
3. DATA
------------------------------------------------------------

We analyse galaxies from the SPARC database
(Lelli, McGaugh & Schombert 2016).

Quality selection requires:

• well-resolved rotation curves
• reliable baryonic mass models
• stable fits for Rs.

After filtering, 53 galaxies remain.

For each galaxy we derive:

Rs
    turnover radius from rotation curve fits

Stot
    cumulative stiffness budget

μS
    local stiffness slope

τ
    outer disk extent proxy

r_max
    outer disk radius inferred from the data.


------------------------------------------------------------
4. SIMPLE HORIZON LAW
------------------------------------------------------------

The stiffness framework predicts that Rs should satisfy a simple
horizon relation of the form

    S(Rs) / Stot = f(μS, τ).

Testing this relation across random train/test splits gives

median log RMSE(Rs) = 0.054 dex
median slope ≈ 1.01
median correlation r ≈ 0.984.

This indicates that the turnover radius can be predicted from
structural quantities alone with high accuracy.


------------------------------------------------------------
5. UNIVERSAL MASTER CURVE
------------------------------------------------------------

If Rs represents the true structural horizon, then scaling
rotation curves by Rs should collapse galaxy profiles onto a
universal curve.

Define

    x = r / Rs
    y = V / V_inf

where V_inf is the asymptotic velocity.

Applying this scaling to the SPARC sample produces a universal
curve with out-of-sample errors

median RMSE(y) ≈ 0.064
median point correlation ≈ 0.96.

Thus the predicted Rs successfully organizes the rotation curves.


------------------------------------------------------------
6. GEOMETRIC–STIFFNESS SCALING
------------------------------------------------------------

We next examine how Rs relates to global disk structure.

Neither total stiffness budget nor outer disk extent alone
predicts Rs strongly:

Rs vs Stot
    r ≈ 0.15

Rs vs r_max
    r ≈ 0.38

However, combining both quantities yields a stronger relation

    Rs ∝ r_max * Stot^{-0.40}

with

r ≈ 0.52
RMSE ≈ 0.237 dex.

Fitting the logarithmic relation

    log Rs = A + log(r_max Stot^{-0.40})

gives a slope of

    1.04 ± scatter,

consistent with the predicted slope of unity.

Residual correlations with Stot disappear when this scaling is
used.


------------------------------------------------------------
7. HORIZON INVARIANT
------------------------------------------------------------

The scaling relation implies a structural invariant

    H = (Rs / r_max) Stot^{0.40}.

Across the SPARC subset this quantity shows a narrow
distribution, indicating that the geometric–stiffness relation
captures the dominant structural dependence of Rs.


------------------------------------------------------------
8. RELATION TO BTFR
------------------------------------------------------------

The stiffness framework also provides a bridge to the baryonic
Tully–Fisher relation.

Testing several predictors yields

median BTFR scatter ≈ 0.23 dex

when Rs and the stiffness-derived corrections are included.

This suggests that the structural horizon plays a role in linking
baryonic mass to asymptotic velocity.


------------------------------------------------------------
9. INTERPRETATION
------------------------------------------------------------

The results suggest a two-scale structure for disk galaxies:

outer disk geometry

    r_max

sets the overall spatial scale, while

cumulative stiffness budget

    Stot

determines where within that disk the stiffness horizon forms.

The turnover radius therefore behaves as

    disk size × stiffness correction.

This structure naturally explains why rotation curves collapse
when scaled by Rs.


------------------------------------------------------------
10. CONCLUSION
------------------------------------------------------------

Using SPARC galaxies we tested a structural model in which the
rotation-curve turnover radius is determined by cumulative
stiffness.

The analysis shows:

• Rs can be predicted out-of-sample with ≈0.05 dex accuracy.
• Scaling radii by Rs collapses rotation curves onto a universal
  master curve.
• Rs follows a geometric–stiffness relation

      Rs ∝ r_max Stot^{-0.40}

  that removes residual correlations with stiffness budget.

These findings suggest that the rotation-curve transition scale
may arise from baryonic structure and cumulative stiffness
rather than requiring additional unseen mass components.


